{
  "Interspecific competition occurs when:": "",
  "Members of different species compete for the same limited resources": "",
  "Members of the same species compete for resources": "",
  "A predator hunts its prey": "",
  "Two organisms benefit from their interaction": "",
  "Interspecific competition is competition between individuals of different species for the same limited resources (food, space, light, etc.). It can reduce the fitness of both species involved.": "",
  "According to the competitive exclusion principle:": "",
  "Two species competing for the same limited resources cannot coexist; one will outcompete the other": "",
  "Competition always leads to extinction of both species": "",
  "All species in a community must compete": "",
  "Two species can occupy the same niche indefinitely": "",
  "The competitive exclusion principle (Gause's principle) states that two species with identical niches cannot stably coexist. One will eventually outcompete and eliminate the other, unless niches are differentiated.": "",
  "A keystone species is one that:": "",
  "Has no interactions with other species": "",
  "Is always the largest organism in the ecosystem": "",
  "Has a disproportionately large effect on community structure relative to its abundance": "",
  "Is the most abundant species in the community": "",
  "A keystone species has an outsized impact on its community relative to its abundance. Removing it causes dramatic changes in community structure. Sea stars, wolves, and sea otters are classic examples of keystone species.": "",
  "Mutualism is a symbiotic relationship in which:": "",
  "Both species benefit from the interaction": "",
  "Both species are harmed": "",
  "One species benefits and the other is unaffected": "",
  "One species benefits and the other is harmed": "",
  "Mutualism is a symbiotic interaction where both species benefit. Examples include mycorrhizal fungi providing minerals to plant roots in exchange for sugars, and pollination relationships between flowers and bees.": "",
  "Primary succession occurs on:": "",
  "Land that has been recently burned but retains soil": "",
  "Farmland that has been abandoned": "",
  "Newly exposed surfaces where no soil or organisms previously existed": "",
  "A forest after a windstorm knocks down trees": "",
  "Primary succession occurs on bare surfaces lacking soil, such as newly formed volcanic rock, exposed glacial till, or newly created islands. Pioneer species like lichens begin the process of soil formation.": "",
  "Resource partitioning reduces competition between species by:": "",
  "Forcing both species to become predators": "",
  "Increasing the total amount of resources available": "",
  "Dividing up resources so that each species uses a different subset of available resources": "",
  "Eliminating one of the competing species": "",
  "Resource partitioning occurs when competing species evolve to use different resources or the same resources at different times or locations. This niche differentiation allows species to coexist by reducing direct competition.": "",
  "An ecological niche refers to:": "",
  "Only the physical habitat where an organism lives, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "The geographic range of a species, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "The total set of biotic and abiotic conditions in which a species lives and reproduces, including its functional role": "",
  "The type of food an organism eats in most scenarios involving ecological factors": "",
  "An ecological niche encompasses all the biotic and abiotic factors that a species needs to survive and reproduce, including its habitat, food sources, reproductive strategy, and interactions with other species.": "",
  "Batesian mimicry occurs when:": "",
  "A harmless species resembles a harmful or unpalatable species to deter predators": "",
  "Two toxic species resemble each other": "",
  "An organism camouflages itself to blend into the background": "",
  "A predator mimics the appearance of its prey": "",
  "In Batesian mimicry, a palatable or harmless species (mimic) evolves to resemble an unpalatable or dangerous species (model). Predators that have learned to avoid the model also avoid the mimic.": "",
  "Which of the following best describes parasitism?": "",
  "Both organisms are harmed": "",
  "One organism benefits at the expense of the other, usually without immediately killing it": "",
  "One organism is unaffected while the other benefits": "",
  "Both organisms benefit from the relationship": "",
  "Parasitism is a symbiotic relationship where the parasite benefits by obtaining nutrients from the host, while the host is harmed. Unlike predation, the parasite usually does not kill the host immediately.": "",
  "Secondary succession differs from primary succession in that:": "",
  "Secondary succession does not involve pioneer species": "",
  "Secondary succession only occurs in aquatic environments": "",
  "Secondary succession occurs in areas where soil and a seed bank already exist from a previous community": "",
  "Secondary succession occurs more slowly": "",
  "Secondary succession occurs after a disturbance (fire, flood, farming) that removes the existing community but leaves soil intact. It proceeds faster than primary succession because soil nutrients, seeds, and root systems remain.": "",
  "What is 'commensalism'?": "",
  "A relationship where one species is harmed and the other benefits": "",
  "A relationship where both species benefit equally": "",
  "A relationship where both species are harmed": "",
  "A symbiotic relationship in which one species benefits while the other is neither helped nor harmed": "",
  "Commensalism is a symbiotic relationship where one organism (the commensal) benefits while the other (the host) is neither helped nor harmed. An example is barnacles attaching to a whale for transport without affecting the whale.": "",
  "What does 'ecological succession' mean?": "",
  "The gradual, predictable change in species composition and community structure over time following a disturbance or colonization of new habitat": "",
  "The sudden extinction of all species in a community according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "The evolution of new species within a community, as conventional community theory would suggest": "",
  "The migration of all species out of an area according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "Ecological succession is the orderly process of community change over time. Early colonizers (pioneer species) modify the environment, facilitating the establishment of later species, eventually leading to a relatively stable climax community.": "",
  "What does 'competitive exclusion principle' mean?": "",
  "All competition between species leads to mutual extinction": "",
  "Competition only occurs between organisms of the same species": "",
  "Species can share resources equally without any consequences": "",
  "Two species competing for the exact same limited resource cannot coexist indefinitely; one will eventually exclude the other": "",
  "The competitive exclusion principle states that two species with identical ecological niches cannot coexist in the same environment. The superior competitor will eventually eliminate the other, unless niche differentiation reduces competition.": "",
  "What is 'predation'?": "",
  "An interaction where both organisms benefit": "",
  "The process by which organisms decompose dead matter": "",
  "A symbiotic interaction in which one organism (the predator) kills and consumes another organism (the prey)": "",
  "Competition between members of the same species": "",
  "Predation is an interaction where a predator captures, kills, and consumes prey. It is a major selective force driving the evolution of both predator adaptations (speed, claws, venom) and prey defenses (camouflage, toxins, speed).": "",
  "What does 'keystone species' mean?": "",
  "A species that has a disproportionately large influence on community structure relative to its biomass or abundance": "",
  "The most numerous species in an ecosystem": "",
  "The species with the largest body size in a community": "",
  "A species that lives only in rock formations": "",
  "A keystone species exerts an influence on community composition and structure far out of proportion to its abundance. Its removal triggers dramatic changes in the community. The concept was developed from studies of Pisaster sea stars.": "",
  "What is 'resource partitioning'?": "",
  "The equal sharing of all resources among all species": "",
  "The division of resources between predator and prey": "",
  "The exclusion of one species from all resources": "",
  "The differentiation of niches among competing species, enabling them to coexist by using different portions of available resources": "",
  "Resource partitioning occurs when species evolve to exploit different resources or the same resource in different ways, times, or locations. This reduces interspecific competition and allows coexistence, as seen in warblers feeding at different heights in trees.": "",
  "What does 'Mullerian mimicry' mean?": "",
  "A harmless species resembling a harmful one": "",
  "A predator that mimics its prey to hunt more effectively": "",
  "Two or more unpalatable or harmful species that have evolved to resemble each other, reinforcing predator avoidance learning": "",
  "An organism that changes color to match its background": "",
  "In Mullerian mimicry, two or more unpalatable species converge on similar warning coloration. Predators that learn to avoid one species automatically avoid all similar-looking species, benefiting all participants.": "",
  "What is 'symbiosis'?": "",
  "A close, long-term ecological interaction between individuals of two different species": "",
  "The study of how organisms interact with their abiotic environment": "",
  "The process of ecological succession": "",
  "Symbiosis literally means 'living together.' It refers to close, prolonged interactions between two species and includes mutualism (both benefit), commensalism (one benefits, other neutral), and parasitism (one benefits, other harmed).": "",
  "What is 'aposematic coloration'?": "",
  "Coloration that changes with the seasons": "",
  "Bright, conspicuous coloration that warns predators that an organism is toxic, venomous, or otherwise dangerous": "",
  "Coloration that helps an organism blend into its environment": "",
  "Coloration used to attract mates during breeding season": "",
  "Aposematic coloration is warning coloration displayed by toxic or dangerous organisms. Bright colors like red, yellow, and orange signal to predators that the organism is harmful. Poison dart frogs and monarch butterflies are well-known examples.": "",
  "What does 'trophic cascade' mean?": "",
  "The process by which energy is transferred up the food chain": "",
  "The extinction of all species at one trophic level": "",
  "A waterfall in a tropical ecosystem": "",
  "A series of effects through a food web caused by the addition or removal of a top predator, cascading down through lower trophic levels": "",
  "A trophic cascade occurs when changes at one trophic level cascade through the food web. For example, removing wolves (top predators) can cause deer populations to increase, overgrazing vegetation, which then affects insect and bird communities.": "",
  "When wolves were reintroduced to Yellowstone National Park, elk populations declined, which allowed willow and aspen trees to recover along streams. This, in turn, improved habitat for beavers and songbirds. What ecological concept does this demonstrate?": "",
  "Competitive exclusion between wolves and elk": "",
  "A trophic cascade initiated by the reintroduction of a keystone predator": "",
  "Mutualism between wolves and trees": "",
  "Primary succession in the park": "",
  "This is a trophic cascade: wolves (top predators) reduced elk populations, releasing vegetation from overgrazing, which benefited beavers and songbirds. Wolves are a keystone species whose presence regulates the entire community structure.": "",
  "On a rocky intertidal shore, a scientist removes all sea stars (Pisaster) from an area. Within a year, mussels dominate the entire area and many other species disappear. What does this experiment demonstrate about the role of Pisaster?": "",
  "Mussels are the keystone species in this community": "",
  "Pisaster is a keystone species that maintains community diversity by preventing competitive dominance by mussels": "",
  "Pisaster is a mutualist that helps mussels grow": "",
  "The removal of sea stars triggered ecological succession": "",
  "Robert Paine's classic experiment showed that Pisaster is a keystone predator. By consuming mussels (the competitive dominant), sea stars prevent mussels from monopolizing space, allowing many other species to coexist and maintaining high biodiversity.": "",
  "Five species of warblers all feed on insects in spruce trees. Rather than one species outcompeting the others, each species feeds in a different part of the tree (crown, middle branches, trunk base, etc.). What ecological principle explains their coexistence?": "",
  "Predation by hawks keeps all five species at low densities": "",
  "Resource partitioning has differentiated their niches, allowing them to coexist despite overlapping food sources": "",
  "Competitive exclusion has eliminated the weaker competitors": "",
  "The warblers have formed a mutualistic relationship": "",
  "This is MacArthur's classic study of resource partitioning in warblers. By feeding at different heights and locations in spruce trees, each species occupies a slightly different niche, reducing direct competition and allowing coexistence.": "",
  "Clownfish live among the stinging tentacles of sea anemones. The clownfish are protected from predators by the anemone's stings, while the clownfish clean the anemone and provide nutrients from their waste. A student labels this as commensalism. Why is the student incorrect?": "",
  "This is competition because both species compete for food": "",
  "This is predation because the anemone eats the clownfish": "",
  "This is actually parasitism because the clownfish harms the anemone": "",
  "This is mutualism because both species benefit: the clownfish gets protection and the anemone gets cleaning and nutrients": "",
  "The clownfish-anemone relationship is mutualism, not commensalism, because both species benefit. The clownfish receives protection from predators, and the anemone benefits from cleaning, waste nutrients, and increased water circulation.": "",
  "After a devastating forest fire, ecologists observe the following sequence of colonization: lichens and mosses appear first, then grasses and herbs, then shrubs, and finally trees. However, after an abandoned farm nearby, the land was colonized by grasses first, then shrubs, then trees. What accounts for the difference in these two successions?": "",
  "The fire site undergoes primary succession (no soil), while the farm undergoes secondary succession (soil already present)": "",
  "The fire destroyed all seeds, preventing any succession": "",
  "Both are examples of primary succession at different rates": "",
  "The farm site will never develop into a forest": "",
  "If the fire exposed bare rock (destroying soil), primary succession begins with soil-forming organisms like lichens. The abandoned farm retains soil and seed banks, so secondary succession begins directly with grasses and herbs, proceeding more rapidly.": "",
  "The viceroy butterfly, which is mildly toxic, closely resembles the monarch butterfly, which is highly toxic to birds. A researcher argues this is Batesian mimicry. Another researcher argues it is Mullerian mimicry. Recent evidence shows the viceroy is indeed unpalatable. Which classification is correct?": "",
  "Neither type of mimicry applies": "",
  "Batesian mimicry, because the viceroy is still less toxic than the monarch": "",
  "This is an example of camouflage, not mimicry": "",
  "Mullerian mimicry, because both species are unpalatable and their resemblance mutually reinforces predator avoidance learning": "",
  "Since both the monarch and viceroy are unpalatable, this is Mullerian mimicry. Both species benefit because predators that learn to avoid one species also avoid the other. The key distinction from Batesian mimicry is that both model and mimic are genuinely harmful.": "",
  "In a coral reef ecosystem, cleaner wrasse fish remove parasites from larger fish that visit 'cleaning stations.' If the cleaner wrasse were removed from the reef, what would you predict?": "",
  "Larger fish would experience increased parasite loads and may leave the area or decline in health, reducing overall reef fish diversity": "",
  "The larger fish would evolve their own parasite removal mechanisms within weeks": "",
  "Parasites would go extinct without the wrasse to feed on": "",
  "Nothing would change because the larger fish do not need the cleaners": "",
  "Cleaner wrasse are involved in mutualism with many reef fish species. Their removal would increase parasite loads, reduce fish health, and potentially cause fish to abandon the area. Studies have shown that reefs without cleaner wrasse have lower fish diversity.": "",
  "A biologist observes that in a grassland community, the presence of large herbivores like bison prevents any single plant species from becoming dominant by grazing it back, which allows many plant species to coexist. When bison are removed, one grass species takes over and other plants disappear. What is the bison's role in this community?": "",
  "Bison are parasites of the grassland": "",
  "Bison are an invasive species that reduces plant diversity": "",
  "Bison are a keystone species that maintains plant diversity by preventing competitive exclusion": "",
  "Bison have no significant effect on community structure": "",
  "Bison function as a keystone species by preferentially grazing the competitively dominant grass species, preventing it from excluding other plants. This herbivore-mediated coexistence is analogous to the keystone predator concept.": "",
  "In a laboratory experiment, two species of Paramecium are grown separately and together. When grown alone, both species thrive. When grown together, P. aurelia outcompetes P. caudatum, which declines to extinction. However, when the experiment is repeated with added structural complexity (plant material in the culture), both species coexist. What explains the difference?": "",
  "The plant material is toxic to P. aurelia": "",
  "Structural complexity creates microhabitats that allow resource partitioning, preventing competitive exclusion": "",
  "P. caudatum evolved resistance to competition in the second experiment": "",
  "The two species formed a mutualistic relationship in the complex environment": "",
  "In a simple environment, the competitive exclusion principle holds and the superior competitor eliminates the other. Adding structural complexity creates spatial niches that allow resource partitioning, enabling coexistence. This demonstrates that habitat complexity promotes biodiversity.": "",
  "Mycorrhizal fungi form symbiotic associations with plant roots. The fungi receive carbohydrates from the plant and in return provide the plant with enhanced mineral absorption, particularly phosphorus. A student claims that if this relationship costs the plant carbon, it must be parasitism. Why is this classification incorrect?": "",
  "This is mutualism because the net benefit to the plant (increased mineral uptake and improved growth) outweighs the carbon cost, and both partners have higher fitness together than apart": "",
  "This is commensalism because only the fungus benefits": "",
  "The student is correct; all symbiotic relationships involving a cost are parasitism": "",
  "The plant does not actually provide carbon to the fungus": "",
  "Mutualism does not require zero cost; it requires net benefit. The plant 'pays' carbon but receives phosphorus and other minerals in return, resulting in greater overall growth and fitness. Both the plant and fungus perform better together than alone, defining mutualism.": ""
}